  "raw_text": {
    "type": "doc",
    "attrs": {
      "meta": {},
      "suggestionId": null,
      "suggestionTimestamp": null,
      "suggestionUserId": null,
      "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
      "suggestionKind": null,
      "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
    },
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "n94i4o680z5",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Social learning broadly refers to learning that occurs through the learner\u2019s social experiences, such as observing or interacting with others. In contrast, asocial or individual learning refers to learning that takes place in the absence of social input, such as through the exploration of one\u2019s physical environment. Although many nonhuman species exhibit some forms of social learning, it has gained particular attention in cognitive science due to its role in language acquisition and transmission of cumulative culture. In some cases, social learning can be as simple as an individual observing and reproducing the behavior of another. Social learning in humans, however, can also manifest in more complex ways. In particular, human social learning often occurs in communicative contexts; through the use of language and deliberate teaching, humans can effectively communicate abstract, causal knowledge about the world, complex skills, and social norms. Many societies also leverage cultural institutions such as schools and other forms of formal and informal education to facilitate social learning at scale. Although there is some cultural and individual variability, social learning is ubiquitous, emerges early in life, and continues throughout the lifespan."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 1,
          "fixedId": "",
          "id": "history",
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "strong"
              }
            ],
            "text": "History"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "nf5t30w6e1x",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The idea that humans learn from others has been recognized in ancient philosophy, dating back to Confucius (551\u2013479 BCE)\u00a0and Plato (429\u2013347 BCE). In particular, Aristotle (384\u2013322 BCE) noted the early-emerging human proclivity for imitation and its role in language learning ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "ner40peuvxk",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"n0dykvpsrsp\" data-reactroot=\"\">Shields, C. (2023). Aristotle. In E. N. Zalta &amp; U. Nodelman (Eds.), <em>The Stanford encyclopedia of philosophy</em> (Winter 2023 ed.). Retrieved from <a href=\"https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/win2023/entries/aristotle/\">https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/win2023/entries/aristotle/</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Shields, 2023",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "). In modern psychology, "
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "ndo59fy37re",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"n2ydn1s0aut\" data-reactroot=\"\">Vygotsky, L. S. (1978). <em>Mind in society: The development of higher psychological processes</em>. Harvard University Press.</p>",
              "customLabel": "Vygotsky (1978)",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and "
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "n6siaw24aip",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"n13rdfr774c\" data-reactroot=\"\">Bandura, A. (1977). <em>Social learning theory</em>. Prentice Hall.</p>",
              "customLabel": "Bandura (1977)",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " are among the pioneers who emphasized the importance of social and environmental influences on learning.\u00a0"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "nj4so0759lq",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Social learning has often been characterized as a relatively passive process in which a learner benefits from observing a model\u2019s behavior. This simple characterization has been useful in studying social learning in nonhuman species or modeling the process of cultural transmission over multiple generations at the population level ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "n3zsae34iqn",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"na92pcobaws\" data-reactroot=\"\">Rendell, L., Boyd, R., Cownden, D., Enquist, M., Eriksson, K., Feldman, M. W., Fogarty, L., Ghirlanda, S., Lillicrap, T., &amp; Laland, K. N. (2010). Why copy others? Insights from the social learning strategies tournament. <em>Science</em>, <em>328</em>(5975), 208\u2013213. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1126/science.1184719\">https://doi.org/10.1126/science.1184719</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Rendell et al., 2010",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "; "
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nve1vdlymsm",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"n3gjlvlqujk\" data-reactroot=\"\">Thompson, B., van Opheusden, B., Sumers, T., &amp; Griffiths, T. L. (2022). Complex cognitive algorithms preserved by selective social learning in experimental populations. <em>Science</em>, <em>376</em>(6588), 95\u201398. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1126/science.abn0915\">https://doi.org/10.1126/science.abn0915</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Thompson et al., 2022",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "). In humans, however, social learning is often active, communicative, and context dependent; young children ask questions and seek social input from others, share their own knowledge with others, and consider various factors to decide when or from whom to learn (e.g., "
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "n3jm47e5bq9",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"n2vchh31eim\" data-reactroot=\"\">Gergely, G., Bekkering, H., &amp; Kiraly, I. (2002). Rational imitation in preverbal infants. <em>Nature</em>, <em>415</em>(6873), 755.</p>",
              "customLabel": "Gergely, Bekkering, & Kiraly, 2002",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "; "
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nwsrc0do2or",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"ndti1t5r5wz\" data-reactroot=\"\">Harris, P. L. (2012). <em>Trusting what you\u2019re told: How children learn from others</em>. Harvard University Press.</p>",
              "customLabel": "Harris, 2012",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "). Today, how humans learn from others and help others learn is an active area of research that employs a range of methodological approaches, including behavioral experiments with children and adults, computational modeling, and neuroimaging."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 1,
          "fixedId": "",
          "id": "core-concepts",
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "strong"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Core concepts"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "nmygo1m6uu6",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Imitation has been extensively studied as a form of social learning in which a learner observes and reproduces a model\u2019s behavior. Compared to emulation,"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "strong"
              }
            ],
            "text": " "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "which refers to modeling the goal rather than the action itself, imitation often emphasizes re-enactment of the observed action. While imitation emerges early in life, studies suggest that even infants show rational imitation rather than indiscriminate re-enactment, meaning that they tend to imitate\u2014rather than emulate\u2014when the action is considered as a rational means toward the goal ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nksy4npdo34",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"n2vchh31eim\" data-reactroot=\"\">Gergely, G., Bekkering, H., &amp; Kiraly, I. (2002). Rational imitation in preverbal infants. <em>Nature</em>, <em>415</em>(6873), 755.</p>",
              "customLabel": "Gergely, Bekkering, & Kiraly, 2002",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "). In some contexts, children may also re-enact actions that are clearly unnecessary for the goal (overimitation; "
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "n4ij3gj462d",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"n36ueplnycz\" data-reactroot=\"\">Lyons, D. E., Young, A. G., &amp; Keil, F. C. (2007). The hidden structure of overimitation. <em>Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences</em>, <em>104</em>(50), 19751.</p>",
              "customLabel": "Lyons, Young, & Keil, 2007",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "), which may have implications for acquiring cultural practices or complex sequences of actions that are causally opaque, such as rituals or skills that serve functions that are not obvious to a na\u00efve observer.\u00a0\u00a0"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "nxj4fp1bkly",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Social learning is particularly crucial for language acquisition; at the same time, language acquisition enables children to leverage verbal communication to learn about the world [see "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "link",
                "attrs": {
                  "href": "https://oecs.mit.edu/pub/xohbfbix",
                  "title": null,
                  "target": null,
                  "pubEdgeId": null
                }
              }
            ],
            "text": "Language Acquisition"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "]. While young children generally tend to trust information provided by adults, they also become increasingly adept at reasoning about others\u2019 knowledge to decide whom to trust (epistemic trust, or trust in testimony; "
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nqgce6ec01i",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"nrr0n8jjj4s\" data-reactroot=\"\">Harris, P. L., Koenig, M. A., Corriveau, K. H., &amp; Jaswal, V. K. (2018). Cognitive foundations of learning from testimony. <em>Annual Review of Psychology</em>, <em>69</em>(1), 251\u2013273. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1146/annurev-psych-122216-011710\">https://doi.org/10.1146/annurev-psych-122216-011710</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Harris et al., 2018",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ").\u00a0"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "nefu4hssxpy",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "On the flip side of learning from others is facilitating others\u2019 social learning via informing, or teaching ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nbsd5fkzvom",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"njza82a44t8\" data-reactroot=\"\">Kline, M. A. (2015). How to learn about teaching: An evolutionary framework for the study of teaching behavior in humans and other animals. <em>Behavioral and Brain Sciences</em>, <em>38</em>, e31. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1017/S0140525X14000090\">https://doi.org/10.1017/S0140525X14000090</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Kline, 2015",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "). From joint attention and simple communicative gestures (e.g., pointing) [see "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "link",
                "attrs": {
                  "href": "https://oecs.mit.edu/pub/usvwqp80",
                  "title": null,
                  "target": null,
                  "pubEdgeId": null
                }
              }
            ],
            "text": "Gesture"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "] to pedagogical demonstrations and verbal instructions, the human ability to help others learn by communicating their knowledge undergoes significant developmental change throughout early childhood.\u00a0"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 1,
          "fixedId": "",
          "id": "questions-controversies-and-new-developments",
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "strong"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Questions, controversies, and new developments"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "nop8eihwn4v",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Rather than indiscriminately copying observed behaviors, many species, including humans, exhibit selective social learning. Yet, theories differ in how they explain the mechanisms that underlie such decisions. Some accounts are grounded in the idea that different species have evolved different social learning strategies triggered by specific cues (e.g., the body size or age of the model; "
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nras17x5iqw",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"n2tk7zjhdnk\" data-reactroot=\"\">Kendal, R. L., Boogert, N. J., Rendell, L., Laland, K. N., Webster, M., &amp; Jones, P. L. (2018). Social learning strategies: bridge-building between fields. <em>Trends in Cognitive Sciences</em>, <em>22</em>(7), 651\u2013665. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1016/j.tics.2018.04.003\">https://doi.org/10.1016/j.tics.2018.04.003</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Kendal et al., 2018",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "); others appeal to domain-general learning mechanisms, such as associative learning or reinforcement learning, that allow learners to prioritize learning from those whose actions are more successful or yield higher rewards ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nvawuv6eymw",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"njnhw6jm4rk\" data-reactroot=\"\">Heyes, C. (2015). When does social learning become cultural learning? <em>Developmental Science</em>, <em>20</em>(2), e12350-14. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1111/desc.12350\">https://doi.org/10.1111/desc.12350</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Heyes, 2015",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "; "
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "n3sfw1nziuy",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"nr064mndkqv\" data-reactroot=\"\">Olsson, A., Knapska, E., &amp; Lindstr\u00f6m, B. (2020). The neural and computational systems of social learning. <em>Nature Reviews Neuroscience</em>, <em>21</em>(4), 197\u2013212. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1038/s41583-020-0276-4\">https://doi.org/10.1038/s41583-020-0276-4</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Olsson, Knapska, & Lindstr\u00f6m, 2020",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ").\u00a0"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "n1ysff02kbc",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Given the complexity of human social behavior, it is unlikely that a single mechanism is responsible for all aspects of social learning. As such, different theoretical accounts have emphasized various aspects of human cognition to explain what makes human social learning so distinctive and powerful. Natural pedagogy refers to the idea that humans are predisposed to interpret social input as generalizable, especially when it is highlighted by ostensive cues such as eye gaze and child-directed speech ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "n3lm649bpyz",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"nabks6xbahl\" data-reactroot=\"\">Csibra, G., &amp; Gergely, G. (2009). Natural pedagogy. <em>Trends in Cognitive Sciences</em>, <em>13</em>(4), 148\u2013153.</p>",
              "customLabel": "Csibra & Gergely, 2009",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "). The human proclivity for joint attention, teaching, and cooperative communication may also help cultural knowledge to accumulate and evolve over time, giving rise to the ratchet effect"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "strong"
              }
            ],
            "text": " "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "neqa889nopj",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"nry38zqdi52\" data-reactroot=\"\">Tomasello, M., Kruger, A. C., &amp; Ratner, H. H. (1993). Cultural learning. <em>Behavioral and Brain Sciences</em>, <em>16</em>(3), 514\u2013515. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1017/S0140525X00031277\">https://doi.org/10.1017/S0140525X00031277</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Tomasello, Kruger, & Ratner, 1993",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "), in which cultural knowledge tends to accumulate across generations. Other accounts (e.g., inferential social learning, "
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "n3ax6c34zu1",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"nd8vydkkkeq\" data-reactroot=\"\">Gweon, H. (2021). Inferential social learning: Cognitive foundations of human social learning and teaching. <em>Trends in Cognitive Sciences</em>, <em>25</em>(10), 896\u2013910. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1016/j.tics.2021.07.008\">https://doi.org/10.1016/j.tics.2021.07.008</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Gweon, 2021",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ") emphasize early-emerging inferential abilities, suggesting that humans draw rich inferences from both individual and social experiences and, in particular, leverage mental-state reasoning in social contexts [see "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "link",
                "attrs": {
                  "href": "https://oecs.mit.edu/pub/8q02cvue",
                  "title": null,
                  "target": null,
                  "pubEdgeId": null
                }
              }
            ],
            "text": "Theory of Mind"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "] to learn from others and help others learn.\u00a0"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 1,
          "fixedId": "",
          "id": "broader-connections",
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "strong"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Broader connections"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "nmtc7vyf1n0",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Social learning has immediate connections to topics in cognitive science, such as cognitive development, social cognition (in particular theory of mind), and animal cognition."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "nt8ncbqgdwe",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Social learning in humans can also be studied in varying timescales (from early development to evolutionary processes), scope (from specific contents such as word learning or causal reasoning to its role in culture and society), and levels of analysis (from neural and cellular mechanisms to multiagent environments). As such, social learning is a topic of interest in many other fields that deal with human behavior, including anthropology, linguistics, education, evolutionary biology, economics, and artificial intelligence. "
          }
        ]
      },
